  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface for Envoy Shin, Registrar of the Temple, Going to Court
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the eighth spring of the Emperor's reign, in the second moon, he cast out those who monopolized the Premier's power and issued a great proclamation across the realm, renewing governance and refining the transformative influence. The court grew crystalline, discipline became resolute. Wherever sun and moon shed their light, all creatures with blood and breath danced and sang hymns to the Sacred Virtue. On the seventeenth day of the fourth moon, a grand gathering was to convene at the Imperial Capital to celebrate the Heavenly Longevity Festival.

    The officials of Koryo said among themselves: "The Son of Heaven possesses benevolence and sagacity; his ministers embody loyalty and integrity. They advance the worthy and remove the treacherous, promote benefit and eliminate harm, so that nothing lacks its proper place. Though our kingdom is small, we have long offered our service. Yet we have received the exceptional regard of the present sovereign, and thus may trust that our nation will find peace and our people contentment, that ruler and minister rejoice together, and that the state grows ever more steadfast. Surely this year's assembly will surpass all former gatherings. None but the virtuous and talented, whose names are known to the court, may be sent forth to the palace."

    Therefore, Qi, the Minister of Rites and Records, was appointed as envoy, and Shin, the Registrar of the Bureau of Carriages, was chosen as his assistant to depart. All who know Shin have composed verses, and they requested that I provide this preface.

    One who serves in distant lands without bringing dishonor upon his sovereign's commission may be called a true scholar. How much more so for one who bears tribute to pay homage before the throne of brilliant majesty? You must conduct yourself with reverence and care. Your journey will see you supporting the new ruler, entering to offer congratulations at the imperial court, and upon your return, consulting on matters of state. May the sacred edicts be received anew, bright as washed silk. How then could one not proceed with reverence and care? None knows you as I do, and thus I speak these words.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Heavenly Longevity Festival' (天壽節) was an important state occasion celebrating the Emperor's reign and longevity.
  - key: ''
    value: This preface was written to accompany poems celebrating the envoy Shin's diplomatic mission to the Yuan court during the high period of Koryo-Yuan relations.
